===Etymology 1===
From {{inh|en|enm|hele}}, {{m|enm|heel}}, from {{inh|en|ang|hÄ“la}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*hanhilaz}} (compare North Frisian {{m|frr|hael}}, Dutch {{m|nl|hiel}}, {{cog|da|-}} and {{cog|no|hÃ¦l}} Swedish {{m|sv|hÃ¤l}}), diminutive of {{der|en|gem-pro|*hanhaz||hock}}, equivalent to {{suffix|en|hock|le|nocat=1}}. More at {{l|en|hock}}.

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}
[[File:Girls_heel.jpg|thumb|right|A girl's heel]]
[[File:Jud-teisho.svg|thumb|'''heel''' of the hand]]
[[Image:Caraway_bread.jpg|thumb|right|Heel of a loaf of rye bread]]

# {{lb|en|anatomy}} The rear part of the [[foot]], where it joins the [[leg]].
#* {{rfdate|and other bibliographic particulars}} {{w|John Denham (poet)|John Denham}}
#*: He [the stag] calls to mind his strength and then his speed, / His winged '''heels''' and then his armed head.
# The part of a [[shoe]]'s [[sole]] which supports the foot's heel.
# The rear part of a [[sock]] or similar covering for the foot.
# The part of the [[palm]] of a hand closest to the [[wrist]].
#: {{ux|en|He drove the '''heel''' of his hand into the man's nose.}}
# {{lb|en|usually plural}} A woman's [[high-heeled]] shoe.
#* '''2008''', Kwame Shauku, ''Wonderful Williams and the Magnificent Seven'' (page 257)
#*: She'd been wearing '''heels''', and fell backward off her right '''heel''' and twisted or broke her ankle.
#* '''2011''', Candace Irvine, ''A Dangerous Engagement''
#*: Opting to improve her odds of making it up the stairs and into the privacy of her room, she kicked off her left '''heel''', and then her right before leaning down to scoop them up.
#* '''2015''', Alex Blackmore, ''Killing Eva''
#*: Flat shoes. As she pushed off her left '''heel''' and pressed the sole of her foot to the cold floor she looked forward to them.
# {{lb|en|firearms}} The back, upper part of the [[stock]].
# The last or lowest part of anything.
#: {{ux|en|the '''heel''' of a mast}}
#: {{ux|en|the '''heel''' of a vessel}}
#* {{rfdate|and other bibliographic particulars}} {{w|Anthony Trollope}}
#*: the '''heel''' of a hunt
# {{lb|en|US|Ireland}} A [[crust]] end-piece of a [[loaf]] of [[bread]].
#* {{rfdate|and other bibliographic particulars}} Sir {{w|Walter Scott}}
#*: the '''heel''' of the white loaf
# {{lb|en|US}} The [[base]] of a [[bun]] sliced in half lengthwise.
#* '''1996''', Ester Reiter, ''Making Fast Food: From the Frying Pan Into the Fryer'' (page 100)
#*: The bottom half, or the bun '''heel''' is placed in the carton, and the pickle slices spread evenly over the meat or cheese.
# A [[contemptible]], [[inconsiderate]] or [[thoughtless]] person.
# {{lb|en|slang|professional wrestling}} A [[headline|headlining]] wrestler regarded as a "bad guy," whose ring persona embodies villainous or reprehensible traits and demonstrates characteristics of a [[braggart]] and a [[bully]].
#* '''1992''', Bruce Lincoln, ''Discourse and the Construction of Society'' (page 158)
#*: Freedman began his analysis by noting two important facts about professional wrestling: First, that '''heels''' triumph considerably more often than do babyfaces{{...}}
# {{lb|en|card games}} The [[card]]s set aside for later use in a [[patience]] or [[solitaire]] game.
# Anything resembling a human heel in shape; a [[protuberance]]; a [[knob]].
# {{lb|en|architecture}} The lower end of a [[timber]] in a [[frame]], as a [[post]] or [[rafter]].
# {{lb|en|specifically|US}} The [[obtuse]] angle of the lower end of a rafter set sloping.
# {{lb|en|architecture|workman slang}} A [[cyma reversa]].
#: {{rfquotek|Gwilt}}
# {{lb|en|carpentry}} The short side of an angled cut.
# {{lb|en|golf}} The part of a [[club]] [[head]]'s [[face]] nearest the [[shaft]].
# In a [[carding machine]], the part of a [[flat]] nearest the [[cylinder]].

